Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps only 20 steps from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the guidebooks say.
The building encircles the ends of the platforms, each with a tower at the front corner, and looks like a German town hall in the countryside.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is a little sloppy.
However, looking at the interior of the vaulted ticket office, it is obvious what a large enterprise this was the westernmost gateway.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the "late future" of conquests, wanted to achieve its ambitions of conquest of the Middle East with the help of this railroad from Damascus through Baghdad to present-day Saudi Arabia.
German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
Its railway lines were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
Relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
The Hyderpasha station was no better.
In 1917, a munitions train exploded and destroyed the beautifully constructed roof of the building.
According to Turkish sources, it was a sabotage operation.
Since then, it has slowly collapsed, and history has gone far beyond it.
At the same time, today, as the gateway to Anatolia and the whole eastern region, it serves - at least symbolically - as Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon.
The Justice and Development Party in government – the AKP – has developed a completely new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The new policy is characterized by commitment.
It is remarkable that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian groups of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq, with Iran, and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to assess the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the AKP’s leading foreign policy experts, the Turkish MP, Suat Kinikliogl.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours of tumult, which gave me the rhythm of the famous documentary about the old world, "The Night Mail" - I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is intended as a symbol of the new secular state, which turns its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the well-known AKP with Islamic roots represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This gave rise to some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern building made of stone and steel, specially designed for this purpose - located in a developing suburb, between semi-finished shopping malls and cafes. In the latter, middle managers in suits - men and women alike - meet to do business early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have been fit for a right-centred politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit and a tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry with him.
“The party’s foreign policy objective is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War has upset order,” he said.
Turkey is isolated from its rear.
Today he had to turn east and west at the same time.
He couldn't choose between the two.
He had to open in both directions.
"But is it possible that sooner or later you will be forced to make a choice?"
"Turkey has never wanted to face a choice."
He then stressed what almost everyone I have spoken to here has almost automatically repeated: Turkey’s relations with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea countries, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey itself.
It is as if they are trying to convey the message that, in a figurative sense, along with Turkey, the whole of Europe can travel to Asia and the Middle East on those railway lines to the east.
When I was again at the Hydarpasha station, after another night, mostly awake, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conura, the two German gentlemen who had watched the restoration of this magnificent building 100 years ago.
How they would have been surprised to learn that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East are now largely in Turkey’s hands.
And as I waited in the harbour for the ferry to take me back through the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was once called the "sick man of Europe."
At the time, there was no question of which continent would claim this exciting country.
