The collision avoiding "bee car"
To develop accident-prevention technologies, Nissan has drawn inspiration from nature, specifically the bee world, for its new invention.
The Japanese company has designed a robot that imitates the flight of bees to avoid accidents.
The Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C could be the first step in the development of collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center, in collaboration with the renowned University of Tokyo’s Advanced Science and Technology Research Center, built this small robot in Japan.
Kazuhhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and Research and Development, defines the BR23C as a further expansion of Nissan’s four-level safety protective shell.
The robot enhances the collision avoidance capabilities of the company’s products.
While flying, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety protective shell.
More important than this, however, is the role of the complex eye of the uterus, with which it sees at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions.
To duplicate the function of the complex eye, engineers designed a so-called laser range finder.
The instrument identifies obstacles within a range of up to 2 metres at 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms into a collision avoidance action.
"As soon as the obstacle is detected, the small robot immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid collisions, imitating the movements of the uterus.
What distinguishes the system most from the currently available instruments is that in this case the avoidance maneuver takes place completely automatically.
If not, the robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the reverse maneuver cannot be oriented upwards or downwards, nor can it move diagonally, only in two dimensions and only in the direction of the turnability of the wheels, that is, not in the infinite direction and way, as is the case with bees.
In addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan has also implemented a rotational function in the robot to avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process data every few seconds and respond to it.
No data storage or intuitive logic based on previous manoeuvres is required, so it can work without interruption with just a few dozen KB of memory.
This may sound surprising, but it’s not really Gigabyte, and we’re not even talking about megabyte memory.
This is the first step in the development of an instant collision prevention technology that Nissan estimates will enter production cars within ten years.
The robot runs on lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system could be an additional application to bring the driver to the final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
