Statement by Rafael Correa, Quito
The rebuilding of the republic in the spirit of 21st-century socialism.
This is the joint plan of Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
Following the example of his colleagues and friends, Correa explained her ideas on the new constitution on Sunday.
He succeeded in his mission, as 64% of the voters voted in favour of the referendum, according to the official results, which covered 80% of the votes.
According to this, 28% of the population voted against, 7% of the votes were invalid, while 0.7% of the votes were cast unfilled.
The draft constitution required 50% + 1 vote.
On Sunday, two polls at the exit of the polling stations and a counting by a non-governmental organization proved the huge prevalence of “yes” votes with 63% and 70%, respectively.
Rafael Correa spoke about the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday night.
"The Constitution has been a sweeping victory," he said, thanking the Ecuadorians in Guayaquil, its governor's seat, 280 kilometres southwest of Quito.
As is well known, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez, Morales and Chilean President Michelle Bachelet.
According to a report by the Observatory Mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), the vote took place in a calm atmosphere. The main theme was a 444-point text summarizing the principles of "new socialism" defended by the president.
The proposed constitution puts state power at the service of the economy, preserving the state’s right to “plan development” for a country that basically lives on oil extraction by foreign companies and the currency sent by emigrants.
The draft Constitution of Correa, which was elected in 2006, also strengthens the power of the Head of State, who can obtain a mandate for a maximum of two consecutive terms and has the right to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he intends to take advantage of this opportunity and will compete again for the presidential mandate in February 2009.
The president has already begun introducing free healthcare and education in his country, which has 13.9 million inhabitants and half of the population live below the minimum income.
Finally, the Constitution forbids the presence of foreign troops in the country, which could end the Quito-Washington agreement on the use of the Ecuadorian facility that underpins U.S. anti-drug measures.
19 hostages freed in Chad
An Egyptian squad attacked the kidnappers who took 11 tourists and eight escorts hostage ten days ago.
The hostages are now in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and eight Egyptian escorts were detained in the desert for ten days, from where they were transported unharmed to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
The hostages were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad this morning.
Apparently in good condition, they arrived at the al-Maza military base, which is directly connected to the Cairo International Airport, around 2:30 p.m.
The hostages were banned from speaking to the press and were immediately transferred to a hospital in Maadi, a suburb of Cairo, where they were examined.
The hostages are “healthy” and the kidnappers “have not been paid a ransom,” Egypt’s tourism minister Zoheir Garanna said.
The hostages were captured on September 19, at the foot of Mount Ouanat, in the border region of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, where they participated in an off-road safari.
The group consisted of 11 tourists (five Italian men, five German men and one Romanian woman) and eight Egyptians: two tour guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, which organized the safari.
According to an Egyptian security chief, a 30-member special commando arrived in two helicopters and attacked the hostage takers just before dawn.
"There was a gunfight between the troops, half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled," the leader said.
He also said a total of 150 troops had been sent from the Egyptian Lightning Brigade to Sudan, where they were complemented by German and Italian commandos.
The Italian diplomatic leader Franco Frattini, who is currently in Belgrade, stressed the role of secret agents and special Italian task forces.
“We have to admit that this result could not have been achieved without the professional and effective intervention of our intelligence personnel and action teams,” he said without giving further details.
He also denied paying a ransom for the hostages.
The previous day, the Sudanese army announced that they had intercepted a SUV during a patrol on which the kidnappers were travelling, killing six of them (including the Chadian leader) and arresting two of them.
The military said the hostages were linked to a rebel organization in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the organization immediately denied.
