Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
With partial nationalisation, the Benelux countries are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortison, which was the first European to be in trouble due to the spill-over effect of the U.S. credit market crisis: the three countries are supporting the financial and insurance institution with Hungarian interests with a total of EUR 11.2 billion.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands met at the highest level at the end of the week, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s Competition Commissioner.
In the euro area, Fortis Bank is the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been raging for more than a year, and the decisions taken in the bank’s case can therefore be considered to be a precedent in some respects.
According to the decision made on Sunday night, all three states will acquire nearly half (49 percent) of the bank’s existing assets.
The bank will certainly sell some of its interests, including in particular the activities acquired last year from the Dutch ABN Amró, mainly insurance.
Fortis shares began to fall steeply last week, with serious crisis phenomena at the Institute already in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that with 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to let it go bankrupt.
The company's papers fell by about 12 percent on Friday alone, to a 14-year low.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
At current share prices, the group’s total market capitalisation is around <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>14 billion, but this is not realistic according to the company’s directors.
The board blamed the overseas market uncertainty associated with the adoption of the US <0x24>700 billion package for the fall in Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers had risen slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx appointed a new CEO to the bank.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but so far no one has applied for a meaningful offer.
The Belgian government has already indicated that investors do not have to worry or lose their money.
So far, there has been no panic among the bank’s clients, and the branches have not been attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has a separate branch and has also acquired leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
In the United States, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract based on people’s medical records.
Data protection professionals fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that always makes the use of prescription data subject to the consent of the person concerned.
It has to be in independent hands, or we'll leave the fox to the henhouse," Richard Dicke, the developer of the drug-compliant program, quoted in the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the amount due in the event of damage dependent on the health of the client, and if they consider the risk too high, they do not insure it.
In the past, the person was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only after the result of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: he could easily obtain from pharmacies what drugs he had bought in the past year and a half, based on the customer’s identification number, and the program itself infers from his illness and state of health.
For example, taking high doses of cholesterol lowering medication on a regular basis suggests that your blood lipid levels are practically uncontrollably high, which immediately puts you in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of them also specify a risk multiplier, so the insurer has little to do besides paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include the fact that some drugs can be used for several purposes, for example, some compounds can be used against migraine or heat waves, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter is considered to be a significant risk-increasing factor for business insurers, the former not.
Separate companies have been formed to retrieve and process the data, and they ask the patient’s consent before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies.
They are now obliged to do so by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their failure to do so.
Some companies are now also processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to drug consumption data, so they can provide an even more accurate picture of the health of patients.
More and more companies are gaining access to data, and controlling its use is becoming more and more difficult.
There is a separate Health Data Protection Act, but it only applies to health care providers and insurers.
The Congress has before it a bill that also gives the authorities control over companies specializing in data reporting.
Dick Richard understands that this is not enough: he has therefore developed his program, which would make the transfer of data subject’s explicit consent conditional.
Another issue is that the person concerned can hardly refuse the consent, otherwise the insurers will not conclude a contract with him.
So the chickens are somewhat dependent on the goodwill of the fox.
The Global Menu of Marseille
The EU and India will double trade
As the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, the agenda of the ninth summit has also been dominated by this subject, alongside other largely global issues.
There will also be a French-Indian summit today, where nuclear cooperation will be the main topic.
While the European Union recognises that India is an emerging democratic superpower that should have more say in international affairs, the member states have not yet reached a common consensus on whether to support New Delhi’s permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
This question was not raised at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseilles.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, President of the European Union José Manuel Barroso and High Representative Javier Solana welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double trade flows to more than EUR 100 billion in five years.
Given that trade increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not an overly ambitious target.
In this context, the 26 bilateral civil aviation agreements with India have been legally consolidated, meaning that air traffic could also rise in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance that while the EU is India’s number one trading partner, New Delhi is only the ninth in the EU’s list of partners.
The summit focused on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, as well as terrorism - the latter in all its forms - was condemned on both sides and urged to convene a UN conference.
They also called for the conclusion of the Doha Trade Round, although both have played a large part in the failure to date.
The EU has reaffirmed its commitment to its energy and climate programme, which aims to reduce emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India agreed that the next climate conference should be a global deal to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 percent by 2050.
They also wanted to prevent the rise in food prices, and they supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
The Indian prime minister is headed to the French capital today, where he is preparing to make a deal on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at the bilateral meeting.
In Paris, French companies are expected to be awarded 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
According to the news agency, the agreement would be for 15 years.
More than 300 Italian publishing houses in Frankfurt
Italian publishers have a strong presence at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishing houses will be present at the 60th Buchmesse, the most important international copyright meeting.
This year’s Frankfurt International Book Fair will be attended by 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries, covering a floor area of 171,790 square meters, where more than 403,000 books will be presented.
At the opening ceremony of the Italian Pavilion, the Italian government will be represented by Francesco Maria Giro, Deputy Secretary of State at the Ministry of Cultural Goods and Activities: Italy will occupy an exhibition area of 264 square meters by setting up a single Italia Point.
The opening ceremony will be followed by a press conference in the "Room Struktur" room in the Buchmesse 5.0 pavilion, where data, trends and prospects on the state of Italian publishing will also be presented.
According to the data, the proportion of foreign authors in the Italian publishing market is steadily declining, especially in the field of adult and youth publications.
Billionaire Steve Fossett's plane was found missing a year ago
The remains of billionaire Steve Fossett's plane were found on September 3, 2007.
The wreckage was found on a 3,000-metre-high plateau in the Sierra Nevada Mountains near Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
No human remains were found inside the aircraft.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: “After determining the location of the plane, we sent out a team, and now we can be sure that it was the plane that Steve Fossett flew the day he disappeared,” he said.
The sheriff also confirmed that no human remains were found on the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Department of Transportation Safety (NTSB) said a committee of inquiry had been called in a few hours after the wreck was discovered to identify the plane and determine that it was indeed the Bellanca 8kcab that disappeared on September 3, 2007, the day Fossett left Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, also, in California, near the Nevada border, a couple found some of Fossett's personal belongings near his home in Mammoth Lakes.
Two I.D.s in the name of Fosset, issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, some cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was abandoned a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire set a number of peaks that made him enter history.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he managed to fly around the earth for the first time with a balloon: two weeks of solitary flight.
Three years later, he went around the world by plane, without landing.
Among his many records is the flight over the Andes at an altitude of 15,445 meters, carried out by a co-pilot.
